This paper is likely to belong to the arXiv CS sub-category of computational linguistics (cs.CL) as it deals with selectional preferences in natural language processing. It also involves statistical modeling and machine learning, which are common in the sub-category. 

The paper may also belong to the sub-category of machine learning (cs.LG) as it presents a model that learns selectional preferences for classes of verbs. 

Additionally, the paper may be relevant to the sub-category of artificial intelligence (cs.AI) as it involves machine learning and natural language processing, which are both areas of AI research. 

The sub-category of information retrieval (cs.IR) may also be relevant as the paper discusses the use of selectional preferences for word sense disambiguation, which is a common task in IR. 

Finally, the sub-category of cybernetics (cs.CY) may be relevant as the paper deals with the integration of learned preferences in WordNet, which is a system for organizing and accessing lexical information.
